answer_a:
PRIDE is a database for proteomics datasets that provides users with access to high-throughput experimental data from various sources. To submit a dataset to PRIDE, there are two types of submissions: complete and partial.

Complete submissions ensure that the processed results (including identification data) and the corresponding mass spectra can be parsed, integrated, and visualized by PRIDE. To achieve this, processed identification results need to be provided in a PSI open standard format (either mzIdentML or mzTab). Submitters should follow the PRIDE data policy, which states that all datasets submitted to PRIDE are private by default and can remain private for up to 2 years after being submitted. Once a dataset is released to the public, it can be modified, but this should be done with caution and only after the submitter requests it.

Partial submissions provide processed identification results in other data formats than those indicated above for complete submissions. Submitters can access their own private datasets by using their PRIDE username and password, and additional usernames and passwords are provided to journal editors and reviewers during the manuscript review process.

In general, submitters of proteomics datasets to PRIDE should be aware of the following aspects of our data policy:

* The PRIDE database has a uniform policy of free and unrestricted access to all the datasets deposited once they are released to the public.
* Dataset licenses for PRIDE datasets are under the Creative Commons Public Domain (CC0) License, and all submitters have specifically agreed to these terms during the submission process.
* PRIDE will automatically release datasets to the public upon notification of the corresponding publication, but this can be up to 2 years after submission.
* Private datasets can be modified before they are released to the public, but this should be done with caution.
* Public datasets should not be modified unless it is really unavoidable, based on exceptional reasons.
* Submitters should make sure that the data included in a dataset is consistent, valuable, and correct before it is released to the public.
* Datasets can be released as public or as a combination of public and private datasets.
* The PRIDE team can attach additional files to a dataset to help users understand, retrieve, and reuse them, but these files do not modify the original submitted files in any way.

If you have any questions or need further clarification on the PRIDE data policy or dataset submissions, you can contact the PRIDE team at [ contact@PRIDE.ac.uk](mailto:contact@PRIDE.ac.uk).
